1.1

By hand, compute the expected number of individuals over time in a population with a single initial individual that grows according to equation 3 for \(\lambda = 1.9\), \(\lambda = 2.0\), and \(\lambda = 2.1\), where \(\lambda\) is the finite rate of increase. Enter your data in R using c() for 10 timesteps. For example: lambda_1.9 <- c(1, 1.9) (but with nine more entries). Plot the data as points and use the function points() to present all three trajectories on a single plot. Plot your data as a timeseries, meaning the horizontal axis is time (or timesteps, in this instance).

lam1.9 <- c(1, 1.9, 3.61, 6.859, 13.0321, 24.76099, 47.04588, 89.38717, 169.83563, 322.68770, 613.10663)
lam2.0 <- c(1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128, 256, 512, 1024)

times <- seq(from = 0, to = 10, by = 1)
plot(x = NA, type = "n", xlim = c(0, 10), ylim = c(0, max(c(lam1.9, lam2.0, lam2.1))), xlab = "time", ylab = "Density")
  points(x = times, y = lam1.9, col = "black", pch = 16)
  points(x = times, y = lam2.0, col = "red", pch = 16)
  points(x = times, y = lam2.1, col = "blue", pch = 16)

1.2

Plot the numbers aclculated in exercise 1.1 as ln(\(N\)) versus time. Do this by creating a new object that is the natural log of the data from exercise 1.1. Plot all three growth curves again using the function points(). Calculate and report the equations of the three curves (lines are technically a type of curve, should that be what your data show). To write out math, just put dollar signs around your text: $\lambda = 1.9$ (looks like \(\lambda = 1.9\)).

log1.9 <- log(lam1.9)
log2.0 <- log(lam2.0)
log2.1 <- log(lam2.1)
plot(x = NA, type = "n", xlim = c(0, 10), ylim = c(0, max(c(log1.9, log2.0, log2.1))), xlab = "time", ylab = "log(Density)")
  points(x = times, y = log1.9, col = "black", pch = 16)
  points(x = times, y = log2.0, col = "red", pch = 16)
  points(x = times, y = log2.1, col = "blue", pch = 16)

The three equations are: \(\log (y) = 1.9x + 0\) for \(\lambda = 1.9\), \(\log (y) = 2.0x + 0\) for \(\lambda = 2.0\), and \(\log (y) = 2.1x + 0\) for \(\lambda = 2.1\)

1.3

Derive an equation for doubling time in an exponentially growing population, and derive one for tripling time.

If \(N(t) = N(0)e^{rt}\), and we want to double or triple the initial population, we respectively seek the ratios \(\frac{N(t)}{N(0)} = 2\) and \(\frac{N(t)}{N(0)} = 3\). How long that takes means we must then solve for \(t\). If \(x = e^{rt}\), solving for \(t\) would require taking the log (natural) of both sides, then dividing both sides by \(r\), leaving us with \(\frac{\log (x)}{r} = t\). For doubling time let \(x = 2\) and for tripling time let \(x = 3\).

1.5

The human population on a small island nation is said to be doubling every 20 years. What would be the value of \(r\) (assuming an exponential model)? In \(2 = \frac{N(20)}{N(0)} = e^{r(20)}\), then we are trying to solve for \(r\). In this case, we take the natural log of both sides and divide by \(t = 20\), giving \(r = \frac{\log (2)}{20} = 0.03465736\).

1.6

Using the differential form (i.e., continuous time), suppose that \(r = 0.5\). Compute \(N\) as a function of \(t\), again beginning with a single individual. Do the same for \(r = 1.5\) and for \(r = 1\). Graph all of the results.

# Use the solution to the exponetial equation to solve for N at time t from an inital N of 1 (here, until t = 10)
times <- seq(from = 0, to = 10, by = 0.01)
r0.5 <- 1*exp(0.5*times)
r1.0 <- 1*exp(1.0*times)
r1.5 <- 1*exp(1.5*times)
plot(x = NA, type = "n", xlim = c(0, 10), ylim = c(0, max(r1.5)), xlab = "time", ylab = "Density", las = 1)
  points(x = times, y = r0.5, col = "black", pch = 1)
  points(x = times, y = r1.0, col = "red", pch = 1)
  points(x = times, y = r1.5, col = "blue", pch = 1)

Plot the derivative (which you can approximate by subtracting the current \(N\) from its successive on and dividing by the change in time) as a function of \(N\) for the data calculated in exercise 1.6 (use a small time interval, e.g., 0.01).

len.t <- length(times)
#  len.t # we know how many ts we calcualtes

1.8

From the data calculated in exercise 1.7, divide the estimated derivative by the average number of individuals during the time period, and plot them over time. What is the result, and what does it mean?

der_per.ind0.5 <- diff0.5/r0.5t
der_per.ind1.0 <- diff1.0/r1.0[-len.t]
der_per.ind1.5 <- diff1.5/r1.5[-len.t]
plot(x = NA, type = "n", xlab = "time", ylab = "dNdt / N", xlim = c(0, max(times)), ylim = c(0, .02), las = 1)
  points(x = times[-len.t], y = der_per.ind0.5)
  points(x = times[-len.t], y = der_per.ind1.0, col = "red")
  points(x = times[-len.t], y = der_per.ind1.5, col = "blue")

Dividing the rate of change by the number of individuals gives you the per-capita (per-individual) rate of change. Looking at the per-capita rate of change over time shows that there is no change in the reproductive rate independent the population size (some times there was just a single individual, others there was over 3 million!) . This graphical relationship demonastrates why the section just read is called density-independent change.
